{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ff39c67-429f-4862-b861-864344cf706f","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`** — it's the right choice here.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, your workloads likely need newer manifest/package versions — this command fetches them.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the workloads you already have at their current versions. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n# then rebuild\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` (or `maui-*`) workloads are present, and reinstall if needed with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0714236e-44d1-4895-935a-595455002e64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":266,"requestId":"A42D:3B9434:5DB4EAC:66282E1:69F0041E"},"id":"a252d496-703a-4826-8789-94760f4d2918","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:44.345Z","parentId":"ada33434-a170-4479-a85e-6a22a9eb72c0"}
